\section{\texttt{gmom}: geometric-modulus mean}

\subsection{Use}
\iexec[quiet,trace,stdout=xtract.txt]{grep 'proc gmom' -A3 nstat.chpl}

\lstinputlisting[style=lstchapelf, numbers=none]{xtract.txt}



\subsection{Theory}



\texttt{gmom} is my own humble attempt to generalize the idea of a
geometric mean to sequences containing negative and null values, as well as
positive.

First, consider a sequence $(x_1, x_2, \ldots, x_n)$ containing only
negative values. It is reasonable to define its ``geometric'' mean as
\begin{align}
  \tilde{x} &= -\exp\left[\frac{1}{n} \sum_{i=1}^n \ln(\left|x_i\right|)\right].\label{eq:gmean-neg}
\end{align}
For a sequence containing negative, null, and positive values,
$\ln(\cdot)$ can no longer be used, and the singularity at the origin
needs to be avoided. A function that has those attributes and is
asymptotically equal to $\ln(\cdot)$ for large positive values of its
argument is the \emph{log-modulus} function introduced by
\cite{john1980alternative}:
\begin{equation}
\logmod(x) \equiv \sign(x)\ln(|x| + 1).\label{eq:def-logmod}
\end{equation}
Note that, asymptotically,
\begin{equation}
  \logmod(x) \sim \begin{cases}
    x, & x \sim 0, \\
    \sign(x)\ln(|x|), & x \gg 1,
  \end{cases}
\end{equation}
and that $\logmod(x)$ is odd.

In order to mimic (\ref{eq:gmean-explog}), we need the inverse of $\logmod$:
\begin{align*}
  y &= \sign(x)\ln(|x| + 1),  \\
  \sign(y)y &= \ln(|x| + 1),  \\
  \intertext{(because $\logmod$ is odd)}
  \exp\left(\sign(y)y\right) &= |x| + 1, \\
  \exp\left(|y|\right) &= |x| + 1, \\
  |x| &= \exp\left(|y|\right) - 1, \\
  x &= \sign(y)\left[ \exp\left(|y|\right) - 1\right],
\end{align*}
whence
\begin{equation}
\expmod(x) \equiv \sign(x)\left[ \exp\left(|x|\right) - 1\right]\label{eq:def-expmod}
\end{equation}
is the \emph{exponential-modulus} function.

We are now ready to define the \emph{geometric-modulus} mean:
\begin{equation}
\tilde{x} \equiv \expmod\left[ \frac{1}{n}\sum_{i=1}^n
  \logmod(x_i)\right].
\label{eq:def-gmom}
\end{equation}
Evidently, for a sequence of positive real values where $x_i \gg 1\;
\forall i = 1, \ldots, n$, (\ref{eq:def-gmom}) will produce results
which are very close to (\ref{eq:gmean-explog}). However, if on the
other hand $x_i \ll 1\; \forall i = 1, \ldots, n$, (\ref{eq:def-gmom})
will be very much like the arithmetic mean, which is undesirable. The
solution to always obtain a ``geometric mean''-like behavior for any
sequence (now including possibly null and negative values as well) is
to re-scale before averaging, by means of the following sequence of
operations:
\begin{align}
  \delta &= \frac{\min(|x_i|)}{16}, \qquad x_i \ne 0, \label{eq:delta}\\
  \xi_i &= \frac{x_i}{\delta}, \label{eq:xi}\\
  \tilde{\xi} &= \expmod\left[ \frac{1}{n}\sum_{i=1}^n
    \logmod(\xi_i)\right], \label{eq:tilde-xi}\\
  \tilde{x} &= \delta \tilde{\xi}.\label{eq:tilde-x}
\end{align}
The factor 16 in (\ref{eq:delta}) is arbitrary and is meant to force
all non-null $\xi$ to be ``sufficiently'' far from $\pm 1$.


\section{\texttt{covar}: the covariance}

\subsection{Use}
\iexec[quiet,trace,stdout=xtract.txt]{grep 'proc covar' -A6 nstat.chpl}

\lstinputlisting[style=lstchapelf, numbers=none]{xtract.txt}



\subsection{Theory}

Calculates
\begin{equation}
\Cov\{x,y\} = \frac{1}{n}\sum_{i=1}^n (x_i - \overline{x})(y_i - \overline{y}),
\end{equation}
where $\overline{x}$ is the mean of $\vet{x}$, $\overline{y}$ is
the mean of $\vet{y}$, and $n$ is their size.
Note that you must calculate $\overline{x}$ and $\overline{y}$
\emph{before} calling \texttt{covar}.

