\end{equation}

\section{\texttt{outlimits}: defines limits to detect outliers based
  on the interquartile range}

\subsection{Use}
\iexec[quiet,trace,stdout=xtract.txt]{grep 'proc outlimits' -A4 nstat.chpl}

\lstinputlisting[style=lstchapelf, numbers=none]{xtract.txt}

\subsection{Theory}

Inspired by \cite{merchant1999toward}, \cite{kilpatrick2015decade}, etc.: given an array $\vet{x}$ of
data and a coefficient $\Delta$ ($\Delta = 1.5$ by default, but it can
be modified), proposes the limits
\begin{align}
  x_{min} &= q_1 - \Delta (q_3 - q_1), \\
  x_{max} &= q_3 + \Delta (q_3 - q_1),
\end{align}
where $(q_1,q_2,q_3)$ are the quartiles, $(q_3 - q_1)$ is the
\emph{interquartile range}, and $(x_{min},x_{max})$ is the range outside of
which data are to be considered outliers.

