\subsection{Theory}

Let $\vet{x}$ and $\vet{y}$ be two data arrays containing data points
$(x_i,y_i)$, $i = 1\ldots,n_d$. 
\texttt{init\_lowess} simply calculates normalized $\vet{\bar{x}}$ and
$\vet{\bar{y}}$:
\begin{align}
  x_{min} = \min_i x_i, \\
  x_{max} = \max_i x_i, \\
  \bar{x}_{i} = \frac{x_i - x_{min}}{x_{max} - x_{min}},
\end{align}
and similarly for $\vet{y}$. For this purpose, it calls the private
procedure \texttt{normalize\_array} and stores $\vet{\bar{x}}$ and
$\vet{\bar{y}}$ in the private arrays \texttt{n\_xx} and \texttt{n\_yy}.
It also stores, for further use, the size \texttt{win} of the data
window for local estimates (hereafter, $m$), and the degree
\texttt{deg} of the least-squares regressions in
\texttt{lowess\_estimate} (hereafter, $n$). All the rest is done by
the next procedure, \texttt{lowess\_estimate}.


\section{\texttt{lowess\_estimate}: estimate $\widehat{y}$ at a point $x$ 
  using ordinary least squares}

\subsection{Use}
\iexec[quiet,trace,stdout=xtract.txt]{grep 'proc lowess_estimate' -A2 nstat.chpl}

\lstinputlisting[style=lstchapelf, numbers=none]{xtract.txt}

\subsection{Theory}

Based on the ``observational'' data $\vet{x}$ and $\vet{y}$ passed to
\texttt{init\_lowess}, given an abscissa $x$ (which may or may not be
equal to one of the data points $x_i$ to be used by lowess), we want
to obtain a local estimate $\widehat{y}$  ``through'' the data points.

First, $x$ itself is normalized:
\begin{equation}
\bar{x} = \frac{x - x_{min}}{x_{max} - x_{min}}.
\end{equation}
Now, for all (normalized) data points $\bar{x}_{i}$, calculate the distances to $\bar{x}$:
\begin{equation}
d_i = |\bar{x} - \bar{x}_{i}|, \qquad i = 1,\ldots,n_d.
\end{equation}
This will be used to calculate the weights of the $m$ nearest points
to $x$. We need the indices of the $m$ $x_i$\is\ closest to
$x$. This is done by the private procedure
\texttt{get\_min\_range}. The indices of the $m$ nearest neighbors are
found by \texttt{indxquickselect}, from module \texttt{ssr}, and
returned in the array of \texttk{int}\is\ \texttt{min\_range}
(hereafter $R$),
together with the maximum distance among them $d_{max}$ (in variable
\texttt{maxdist}):
\begin{equation}
d_{max} = \max d_{R_i}, \; i = 1,\ldots, m.
\end{equation}
This allows the calculation of the weights of each data point
$x_{R_i}, \; i = 1, \ldots m$:
\begin{align}
  w(x) &\equiv (1 - |x|^3)^3, \\
  w_i &= w(d_{R_i}/d_{max}).
\end{align}

The $w_i$\is\ will be put in the diagonal of a matrix $\vet{W}$ for
weighted least squares. The statistical model is
\begin{equation}
\widehat{Y} = \beta_0 + \beta_1 \bar{x} + \beta_2 \bar{x}^2 + \ldots +
\beta_n \bar{x}^n.
\end{equation}


We apply the relevant theory without
details. Build the matrices $\met{W}_{m\times m}$ and $\met{X}_{m\times n}$: 
\begin{align}
  W_{ij} &= \delta_{ij}w_i,\label{eq:diag-W}\\
  X_{i,0} &= 1, \\
  X_{i,1} &= \bar{x}_{R_i}\\
  X_{i,j} &= \bar{x}_{R_i}^j.
\end{align}
Note that if $n = 1$, the last line above is not calculated. In
(\ref{eq:diag-W}), $\delta_{ij}$ is Kronecker's delta. The observed
normalized ordinates are
\begin{equation}
Y_i = \bar{y}_{R_i}.
\end{equation}

Now let $\met{A}_{n+1 \times m}$, $\met{B}_{n+1 \times n+1}$
$\met{C}_{n+1 \times m}$ be matrices, $\met{\beta}_{n+1\times 1}$ be a
vector, and calculate a standard weighted
multiple regression:
\begin{align*}
  \met{A} &\leftarrow \met{X}^\tr\met{W}, \\
  \met{B} &\leftarrow \met{A}\met{X},\\
  \met{B} &\leftarrow \met{B}^{-1}, \\
  \met{A} &\leftarrow \met{B}\met{X}^\tr, \\
  \met{C} &\leftarrow \met{A}\met{W}, \\
  \met{\beta} &\leftarrow \met{C}\met{Y}.
\end{align*}
where $\beta_0, \beta_1, \ldots, \beta_n$ are the regression
parameters. Then,
\begin{equation}
\widehat{Y} = \met{\beta}^\tr\met{X}
\end{equation}
is the normalized estimate and
\begin{equation}
\widehat{y} = y_{\min} + \widehat{Y} \times (y_{\max} - y_{\min})
\end{equation}
is the final estimate.

\texttt{lowess\_estimate} makes use of the serial versions of matrix
operations defined in module \texttt{smatrix}. No attempt is made to
calculate faster matrix products which are possible, for
example, using \texttt{gemv} and similar routines from module BLAS.

The main reason for implementing the two lowess procedures serially is
that now the user is supposed to leverage parallelization by calling
\texttt{lowess\_estimate} inside a \texttk{forall} loop:

